The article is a presidential determination and certification regarding the Child Soldiers Prevention Act of 2008. The president determines that it is in the national interest to waive certain provisions of the act with respect to the Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Somalia, Yemen, and Russia. This waiver allows for the provision of International Military Education and Training (IMET) and Peacekeeping Operations (PKO) assistance, as well as the issuance of licenses for direct commercial sales. The president also certifies that the governments of these countries are taking steps to address the issue of child soldiers. The determination and certification will be submitted to Congress and published in the Federal Register.